article.headline: Posey provides scoring punch off Memphis bench
article.linkText: Grizzlies keep rolling with win over Bobcats
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The Charlotte Bobcats have surprised many teams this season by playing pretty well. This time, they surprised themselves by playing really bad. The Bobcats were flat from the start and failed to put up much of a fight Friday night in a 109-89 loss to the Memphis Grizzlies. "It was a sad commentary for a basketball team on our part," Charlotte coach Bernie Bickerstaff said. "We did not play the way we wanted to, and the reason is perplexing to me." Charlotte really struggled in defending Memphis, which led from start to finish, had six players in double figures and had everyone in uniform score at least one point. Pau Gasol led Memphis with 19 points, and James Posey came off the bench to add 17. Shane Battier scored 15, Jason Williams had 14 and Earl Watson and Stromile Swift added 10 each. "We knew this game was by no means a gimme," Battier said. "These guys play really well at home and have beat some pretty good teams here who underestimated them. We gave them a lot of credit coming in." The Grizzlies, who started the season 9-15, have won 10 of their last 13 games. "This was a good team a year ago. They just had to get healthy first and get back to feeling like we can some games again," Memphis coach Mike Fratello said. "Once that happens, I fell like we can be a pretty decent team." Emeka Okafor had 17 points and 12 rebounds for the Bobcats, who struggled from the opening tip. The Bobcats take pride in at least playing hard through their losses. But coming off a two-day layoff since their 100-98 overtime loss at Cleveland on Tuesday night, they hardly seemed fresh. "I don't know what's wrong," forward Gerald Wallace said. "We play good one night and then take the next night off. We're not good enough to that." The Bobcats also let the officials frustrate them. Wallace was called for a fourth-quarter technical foul during a timeout, and his teammates appeared to be hanging their heads in defeat as Bickerstaff argued the call. Bickerstaff was frustrated with the officiating through most of the first half, and it just about boiled over as the teams headed to the locker room for intermission. Memphis threw a long pass downcourt the was deflected as the clock was winding down. Andre Emmett grabbed the ball, but his shot was blocked by Wallace at what appeared to be the buzzer. The officials initially did nothing as the teams headed to the locker room. Then Ron Garretson called Wallace for a foul, and had to review the play to see if it happened before the buzzer. When he determined 0.3 seconds remained and called the teams back, Bickerstaff glared down the court. Emmett made one free throw for a 58-44 Memphis lead, and Bickerstaff almost had to be coaxed off the court by one of his assistants. Bickerstaff refused to blame the officiating for how poorly Charlotte played. "We were bad," he said. "We can't blame the officials. We have to look in the mirror." The Grizzlies used 12-for-19 second-quarter shooting to build their lead. They were bound to cool off, and did briefly in the third quarter. Charlotte trailed just 73-64 with 3:00 to play in the third when Memphis used a quick 11-2 run to pull away. Gasol scored on a basket and free throw, and Posey made a pair of free throws. He then hit a 3, and after a Charlotte turnover, Swift dunked to open an 84-66 lead.

Game notes
Charlotte center Jahidi White was not in uniform because of neck spasms. ... Memphis's Brian Cardinal was out with a sprained right shoulder. ... The Bobcats offered $50 in "Bobcats Bucks" to the fan who filled out the most All-Star ballots during the game. The money could be spent on tickets or in the team store.
